
[1]rob

   ROB, n.

   The inspissated juice of ripe fruit, mixed with honey or sugar to the
   consistence of a conserve.

                                  ROB, v.t.

   1. In law, to take from the person of another feloniously, forcibly and
   by putting him in fear; as, to rob a passenger on the road.

   2. To seize and carry from any thing by violence and with felonious
   intent; as, to rob a coach; to rob the mail.

   3. To plunder; to strip unlawfully; as, to rob an orchard; to rob a man
   of his just praise.

   4. To take away by oppression or by violence.

   Rob not the poor because he is poor. Prov. 22.

   5. To take from; to deprive. A large tree robs smaller plants near it
   of their nourishment.

   6. In a loose sense, to steal; to take privately without permission of
   the owner.

   7. To withhold what is due. Mal 3.
